{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488780"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:57:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:57:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"538"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/538"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.14,0.7,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"538"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48595"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/538"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"538"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33524"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"393"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4227"},{"type":"tags","id":"4228"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"929"},{"type":"contributions","id":"952"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13212"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14777"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42096"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44468"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48595"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 89-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-year history of a pigmented lesion on the right side of his face. It has slowly increased in size over the last three months. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The lesion is smooth and soft to touch, with irregular borders and colour variation ranging from light to dark brown. (Image)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bowen\u0027s disease","Pigmented basal cell carcinoma","Lentigo maligna","Actinic keratosis","Squamous cell carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELentigo maligna\u003C/strong\u003E, formerly known as the Hutchinson melanotic freckle, is the most likely diagnosis in this case. It is a type of melanoma in situ typically found on sun-exposed areas of the head and neck in older patients. The lesion\u0027s characteristics - irregular borders, colour variation from light to dark brown, smooth surface, and slow growth over years - are classical for lentigo maligna. Diagnosis is usually based on clinical, dermoscopic, and histological features, requiring an excisional biopsy for confirmation. Lentigo maligna is considered a pre-invasive, slowly evolving lesion with a lifetime risk of approximately 5% for progression to lentigo maligna melanoma. The preferred treatment is surgical excision with 5-10mm margins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBowen\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an early form of squamous cell carcinoma in situ. It typically appears as a slow-growing, scaly, erythematous plaque, which doesn\u0027t match the description of the pigmented lesion in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPigmented basal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E can present as a pigmented lesion, but it usually has a pearly, rolled border and may have telangiectasia. It tends to grow more rapidly and can be ulcerated, which is not described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActinic keratosis\u003C/strong\u003E presents as rough, scaly patches on sun-exposed skin. While it can occur in older patients, it doesn\u0027t typically present as a smooth, pigmented lesion with colour variation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents as a firm, red nodule or a flat lesion with a scaly, crusted surface. It tends to grow more rapidly than the lesion described and is not typically pigmented.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Where feasible, the preferred treatment option for lentigo maligna is excision with 5-10mm margins.","Lentigo maligna is a type of melanoma in situ typically found on sun-exposed areas of the head and neck in older patients.","Lentigo maligna has a lifetime risk of approximately 5% for progression to lentigo maligna melanoma."],"references":["Kasprzak JM, Xu YG. Diagnosis and management of lentigo maligna: a review. Drugs Context. 2015;4:212281.","Robinson M, Primiero C, Guitera P, Hong A, Scolyer RA, Stretch JR, et al. Evidence-Based Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Patients with Lentigo Maligna. Dermatology. 2020;236(2):111-6.","Sinclair R. Skin checks. Australian Family Physician. 2012;41(7). Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/5a8606ba-b355-4401-ad1d-7fa7052eb9d3/Skin-checks.aspx#:~:text=the%20top%2010%20benign%20lesions,%E2%80%A2%20chondrodermatitis%20nodularis%20helices%20chronicus"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33524"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"538"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18474"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18474","links